The JeuneS3 programme is a partnership framework aligned with the Dutch SRHR policy with a focus on young people (especially girls) and key populations in francophone fragile countries or areas in Africa. The partnership works in Cameroon, Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of Congo and Benin.

Young people aged 10-24 years, with special focus on girls aged 10-14 yrs and key populations in francophone fragile countries or areas in Africa: Cameroon (Extreme North and East) , Central African Republic (CAR) and the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) (Eastern part: North-and South Kivu) and Benin (North).

The Central African Republic (CAR) is emerging from the most violent conflict in its history, following the turmoil and chaos that supersede the government overthrow in March 2013. The crisis, initially politico-military, was transformed into an unprecedented inter-communal conflict. Following OCHA humanitarian update of 15 September 2017, the Central African Republic (CAR) is currently experiencing the worst displacement crisis since the conflict turned sectarian in 2013. 


Earlier on, in 2016, after the visit of Pope Franciscus and the formation of a new government, hopes raised to gain more stability. EU donors decided end 2016 to reserve funds mainly for stabilization and development activities as laid down in the 5-year National Recovery and Peacebuilding Plan (2017 – 2021), and therefor funds reserved for Humanitarian Response are very limited.

For that, JR members are going to the 4th phase of the response.

Partners for Resilience (PfR) is an alliance of humanitarian, development, climate and environmental civil society organisations (the Netherlands Red Cross (lead), the Red Cross Red Crescent Climate Centre, Cordaid, Care Netherlands and Wetlands International) and NGOs in the South. The alliance promotes the application of Integrated Risk Management (IRM) to strengthen communities

The DRA has approved 4mln EUR for an acute drought response in Southern Africa. The response will be in Zambia and Zimbabwe, focused on FSL, WASH and nutrition. Implementation will be done by 8 DRA members: CARE, Cordaid, ICCO, Oxfam, PLAN, Save, SOS, World Vision

Overall: To ensure that young people (YP), especially girls, and key populations are able, motivated and have the opportunity to make informed choices about their sexual and reproductive health (SRH) and that their sexual and reproductive rights are respected. Pathways: 1. YP are respected as important stakeholders in policy formulation and programs on YP SRHR 2. YP are able to make informed decisions about their SRHR 3. YP and KP are able and have the opportunity to use responsive SRH services 4. Social, cultural, legal, policy and gender barriers around YP’s and KP’s SRHR are reduced

Overall objective: support the implementation of UNISDR's Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction, and SDG's 11, 13, 15, to ensure that vulnerable people become more resilient to crises in the face of climate change and environmental degradation. Strategic objectives: ensure increased community resilience through: 1. strengthening partner NGO's and communities in their knowledge and their dialogue capacity on Integrated Risk Management (IRM); 2. embarking on specific IRM dialogue trajectories at local, national and regional levels, focusing on 3 domains: Policy, Investment and Practise

1. Save lives: affected populations confronted with sudden schocks have access to humanitarian assistance that preserves their survival and dignity. 
2. Respect fundamental rights: protection of affected population at risk of violation of their human rights is being reinforced. 

3. Preserve Human dignity: affected population at risk have acces to basic social services and their essential livelihood mechanisms are re-established.

Access: maximum distance to water point 500m, queuing time less than 15min, filling time maximum 3 min/20 litres or as locally agreed. Water access should be during the whole period of implementation unless action is mostly related to building the local water delivery capacity. 
Sufficient: covering basic needs, i.e. 7.5-15 l/p/d or as locally agreed. 

Safe: 1) low risk of faecal contamination, 2) No faecal coliforms detectable in any 100-ml sample, 3) For piped water supplies, or for all water supplies at times of risk or presence of diarrhoea epidemic, water is treated with a disinfectant to achieve free chlorine residual at the tap of 0.5 mg per litre and turbidity is below 5 NTU, 4) If for a short period, water which is contaminated chemically or radiologically is used, no (significant probability of) negative health effect is (likely to be) detected. 
Domestic use: drinking, cooking and personal hygiene (incl. laundry)

Access: ratio (user/facility) of 1 toilet for a max. 20 people, distance < 50 metres from dwellings, or as locally agreed. 
Clean: regular cleaning and maintenance for public facilities.

Dignified: Use of toilets respect cultural preference and is arranged by household(s) and/or segregated by sex. 
Unsafe facilities: unstable (unlined) pits with risk of collapse, pits accessible to vectors, pits contaminating water tables and poorly sited facilities which expose women and girls to attacks, especially at night. 
Functional facility: fully constructed, in working order and properly maintained, of a type and in a location acceptable to intended users, with hand washing facilities and anal cleansing material.
Hygiene promotion/awareness raising activities. Could be training, campaigns, radio broadcasts, flyers etc. Excludes the distribution of Hygiene/dignity kits that should be covered under WHS-I1.

Regular and timely access: 250g soap/p/m for personal hygiene, 200g soap/p/month for laundry. This includes hygiene/dignity kits. Access may be in-kind or though voucher distribution or through unconditional restricted cash to enable beneficiary to buy soap (without compromising access to other basic needs). 
Distributed items need to be culturally acceptable i.e. take into account local practice and expectations.

Basic, safe and dignified: 
- affected individuals have an minimum covered floor area of 3.5m2 per person.  

- all shelter solutions and materials meet locally agreed technical and performance standards and are culturally acceptable. 
- all household (re-)construction is in accordance with safe building practices and standards.
- all household (re-)construction demonstrate involvement of the affected population and/or are culturally acceptable by the affected population.

Unconditional transfers are provided to beneficiaries without the recipient having to do anything in return in order to receive the assistance . Unrestricted transfers can be used entirely as the recipient chooses i.e. there are no restrictions on how the transfer is spent (Definitions of CALP). It can be delivered e.g. through local banks, shops, traders, local money transfer companies, remittance companies and post offices in either one or several instalments.

(Engendered peace): Au cours de cette année 2018 nous avons touché une cible d'environ 31633 personnes pour la trajectoire de la lutte contre les VBG. Les différentes activités ménées (sensibilisations, causeries éducatives, focus groupe, formation formelle et informelle des bénéficiaires/ des différentes parties prenantes, accompagnement,...) nous ont permise de toucher 20301 bénéficiaires directes (13163 Femmes, 7138 Hommes), 11121 bénéficiaires indirectes(8213 Femmes, 2908 Hommes) et 211 bénéficiaires non spécifié (les personnes handicapées, les femmes veuves...)
Nous remarquons que dans le contexte Centrafricain, 67,5% des femmes sont plus toucher dans le cadre de la mise en oeuvre des activités. Ceci peut s'expliquer par le fait que les femmes sont aussi les plus impacter par la crise en RCA et elle sont les première a chercher les voix et moyen pour trouver les solution afin d'attenuer leur souffrance. / (Security and Access to Justice): Au cours de cette année 2018 nous avons touché une cible d'environ 33980 personnes sur la trajectoire d'accès à la justice, 

Toutes nos activités ménées (sensibilisations, causeries éducatives, focus groupe, formation formelle et informelle des bénéficiaires/ des différentes parties prenantes, accompagnement,...nous ont permise de toucher 23492 bénéficiaires directes (15229 Femmes, 8263 Hommes) 10219 bénéficiaires indirectes (6233 Femmes, 3985 Hommes) et 269 bénéficiaires non spécifié (les personnes handicapées, les Personnes sans abris...)
Nous remarquons que dans le contexte Centrafricain, 63,3% des femmes sont plus toucher dans le cadre de la mise en oeuvre des activités. Ceci peut s'expliquer par le fait que les femmes sont aussi les plus impacter par la crise en RCA et elle sont les première a chercher les voix et moyen pour trouver les solution afin d'attenuer leur souffrance.

Engendered peace - WPS: CEPO (Grace John Kenyi, South Sudan) and MFFPS (Catherine Mabobori, Burundi) were able to address the 33rd Pre-Summit Civil Society Consultative Meeting on Gender Mainstreaming in the African Union (GIMAC) held on 3rd and 4th February 2019, and highlight the important peace-building role of women in protection of civilian sites and IDP camps in South Sudan as well as the need to include displaced women in peace building processes. GIMAC 33 bore the theme “Towards Gender-Responsive Durable Solutions to Forced Displacement”. In preparation for SP partner WIPC and Cordaid partners in Burundi, South Sudan, DRC and Uganda were consulted to identify key issues that could be amplified or advocated for during GIMAC based on the work and evidence of these organisations or networks. Partners were invited to speak during the different thematic panels. These issues were discussed and reflected in the final GIMAC recommendations which called for support for displaced women’s to occupy leadership positions in decision-making in IDP and refugee camps. The outcome document also called for the participation of women in the inter-Burundian dialogue and the need for its revival. The AU Women, Gender and Development Directorate received these recommendations to feed into the processes leading up to the AU Heads of State summit.

Security and access to Justice: Two visits to NYC with partners and colleagues which involved 2 partners and 1 local staff of Cordaid from DRC and CAR to share information and recommendations regarding the extension of the mandate of MONUSCO and MINUSCA to permanent representations, NYC-based NGOs and specific UN country teams.

Inclusive Health services: Cordaid and local CSOs in DRC contributed to the design of the national strategy for Universal Health Coverage in DRC.

Extractives: The OECD has been engaging civil society to a much larger degree, following the criticisms that have been raised last year with regards to poor support to civil society participation. Now, from the start,  there has seen much more engagement on the part of the organizing committee to involve civil society. Many actors, not only CORDAID and EURAC, have advocated that  civil society should be more involved in the OECD forum. This has been done by giving civil society more space to comment on the program, more preparatory calls, and more sessions available at the forum, which is a significant change.
